Calibri'><span style='mso-tab-count:1'>          </span>(b)<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>An individual determined to be a probation or
parole violator shall be an ineligible household </span><span style='font-size:
11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif'>member</span><span
style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
Calibri'>. To be considered a probation or parole violator, an impartial party,
as designated by the department, must determine that the individual violated a
condition of probation or parole imposed under federal or state law and that
federal, state, or local law enforcement authorities are actively seeking the
individual to enforce the conditions of the probation or parole, pursuant to 7
CFR 273.11(n)(3).</span><span style='font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

